I81SUBCHAPTER II_ACCESS OF FOREIGN REPRESENTATIVES AND CREDITORS TO THE COURT

I80ÿ1A1509

I89. Right of direct access

I11(a) A foreign representative may commence a case under section 1504 by filing directly with the court a petition for recognition of a foreign proceeding under section 1515.

I11(b) If the court grants recognition under section 1517, and subject to any limitations that the court may impose consistent with the policy of this chapter_

I12(1) the foreign representative has the capacity to sue and be sued in a court in the United States;

I12(2) the foreign representative may apply directly to a court in the United States for appropriate relief in that court; and

I12(3) a court in the United States shall grant comity or cooperation to the foreign representative.

Q04

I11(c) A request for comity or cooperation by a foreign representative in a court in the United States other than the court which granted recognition shall be accompanied by a certified copy of an order granting recognition under section 1517.

I11(d) If the court denies recognition under this chapter, the court may issue any appropriate order necessary to prevent the foreign representative from obtaining comity or cooperation from courts in the United States.

I11(e) Whether or not the court grants recognition, and subject to sections 306 and 1510, a foreign representative is subject to applicable nonbankruptcy law.

I11(f) Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, the failure of a foreign representative to commence a case or to obtain recognition under this chapter does not affect any right the foreign representative may have to sue in a court in the United States to collect or recover a claim which is the property of the debtor.

I53(Added Pub. L. 109ÿ098, title VIII, ÿ1A801(a), Apr. 20, 2005, 119 Stat. 137.)

I80ÿ1A1510

I89. Limited jurisdiction

I11The sole fact that a foreign representative files a petition under section 1515 does not subject the foreign representative to the jurisdiction of any court in the United States for any other purpose.

I53(Added Pub. L. 109ÿ098, title VIII, ÿ1A801(a), Apr. 20, 2005, 119 Stat. 138.)

I80ÿ1A1511

I89. Commencement of case under section 301, 302, or 303

I11(a) Upon recognition, a foreign representative may commence_

I12(1) an involuntary case under section 303; or

I12(2) a voluntary case under section 301 or 302, if the foreign proceeding is a foreign main proceeding.

Q04

I11(b) The petition commencing a case under subsection (a) must be accompanied by a certified copy of an order granting recognition. The court where the petition for recognition has been filed must be advised of the foreign representative's intent to commence a case under subsection (a) prior to such commencement.

I53(Added Pub. L. 109ÿ098, title VIII, ÿ1A801(a), Apr. 20, 2005, 119 Stat. 138; amended Pub. L. 111ÿ09327, ÿ1A2(a)(45), Dec. 22, 2010, 124 Stat. 3562.)

